OLPC Embedded Controller Debug Command Interface
📁 /sys/kernel/debug/olpc-ec/cmd

Date: December 2011
Kernel Version: 3.4
Contact: devel@lists.laptop.org

Description

This debug interface provides a generic command execution channel for interacting with the OLPC Embedded Controller (EC).

It allows user space to:

send raw EC commands
optionally pass arguments
retrieve raw responses from the EC

This interface is primarily intended for debugging and low-level hardware interaction.

⚠️ Scope and Safety
Debug-only interface (debugfs)
No ABI stability guarantees
Unsafe for production automation without strict validation
Command Format (Write Interface)

To execute a command, write to the node using the following format:

CC:N A A A A
Fields
Field	Meaning
CC	Command byte (hex)
N	Expected number of reply bytes
A	Optional argument bytes (hex, space-separated)
Behavior
Command is immediately forwarded to the Embedded Controller
Arguments are optional depending on command type
No strict validation of argument structure at kernel level
Response Format (Read Interface)

After issuing a command, read from the same node:

<hex reply bytes>
Behavior Notes
Returns raw hex bytes from EC response buffer
Response is not strictly tied to the most recent command
May include leftover or pending EC output

This implies:

Reads are stateful but not transactional
Caller must manage synchronization logic in user space
Design Characteristics
1. Weak Coupling Model
Write = command injection
Read = response stream access
No strict pairing guarantee
2. Debug-Oriented Behavior
Prioritizes visibility over correctness guarantees
Intended for firmware and EC debugging workflows
3. Raw Data Exposure
No structured parsing in kernel
All interpretation is delegated to user space tools
Nexo OS Kernel Notes 🧠

In a Nexo OS context, this interface would typically be classified as:

low-level hardware debug channel
suitable for:
EC firmware validation
embedded controller diagnostics
not suitable for:
production device control logic
deterministic command-response systems

Recommended enhancement layer:

add a transaction ID wrapper
introduce command-response binding buffer
optional safe-mode validation layer
Deprecation Status
Status: Active (Debug Interface)
No scheduled removal
